  <discussion>Most records of Rumex longifolius from the Great Plains (Great Plains Flora
        Association 1977; R. B. Kaul 1986) refer to R. pseudonatronatus (J. E. Dawson 1979), which
        can be distinguished from R. longifolius by its narrower leaves, smaller and more distinctly
        triangular inner tepals, and purplish or reddish brown stems at maturity. The two species
        are closely related; they were placed by K. H. Rechinger (1949) in subsect. Longifolii
        Rechinger f.</discussion>
